Project Description:¶

A project from Cement manufacturing domain.

Context:¶

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate and fine aggregate.

Data Description:¶

The actual concrete compressive strength (MPa) for a given mixture under a specific age (days) was determined from laboratory. Data is in raw form (not scaled). The data has 8 quantitative input variables, and 1 quantitative output variable, and 1030 instances (observations).

  • Input Variables:

Cement : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Blast : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Fly ash : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Water : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Superplasticizer : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Coarse Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Fine Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture

Age : day (1~365)

  • Output Variables:

Concrete compressive strength : measured in MPa

Objective:¶

Modeling of strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning

Treating the outliers¶

From the above analysis we know that the independent attributes slag, water, superplastic, fineagg and age does have outliers in them. We will replace those outliers with the median of the respective attributes.

In [102]:
for col_name in concrete_data.columns[:-1]:
    iq_25 = concrete_data[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    iq_75 = concrete_data[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = iq_75 - iq_25
    cut_off = 1.5 * iqr
    low_lim = iq_25 - cut_off
    upp_lim = iq_75 + cut_off
    
    concrete_data.loc[(concrete_data[col_name] < low_lim) | (concrete_data[col_name] > upp_lim), col_name] = concrete_data[col_name].median()

Model creation¶

Scaling of the features¶

As all the predictors in the same scale apart from age, so we will scale the datasets.

In [120]:
scaled_X_train = X_train.copy()
scaled_X_test = X_test.copy()

num_cols = ['cement', 'slag', 'ash', 'water', 'superplastic', 'coarseagg', 'fineagg', 'age']

for i in num_cols:
    scale = StandardScaler().fit(scaled_X_train[[i]])
    scaled_X_train[i] = scale.transform(scaled_X_train[[i]])
    scaled_X_test[i] = scale.transform(scaled_X_test[[i]])
Polynomial Featurization¶

As we will first try to develop some simple models, for that we need to have variables in higher degree as with simple parameters the model is performing very poorly.

In [121]:
rmses = []
degrees = np.arange(1,10)
min_rmse, min_deg = 1e10, 0

for deg in degrees:
    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree = deg, include_bias = False)
    poly_X_train = poly_features.fit_transform(scaled_X_train)
    
    poly_reg = LinearRegression()
    poly_reg.fit(poly_X_train, y_train)
    
    poly_X_test = poly_features.fit_transform(scaled_X_test)
    poly_predict = poly_reg.predict(poly_X_test)
    poly_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, poly_predict)
    poly_rmse = np.sqrt(poly_mse)
    rmses.append(poly_rmse)
    
    if min_rmse > poly_rmse:
        min_rmse = poly_rmse
        min_deg = deg
        
print('Best degree {} with RMSE {}'.format(min_deg, min_rmse))
        
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
ax.plot(degrees, rmses)
ax.set_yscale('log')
ax.set_xlabel('Degree')
ax.set_ylabel('RMSE')

Best degree 3 with RMSE 6.016097316280968
Out[121]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'RMSE')

Thus, for degree = 3, Linear Regression yields the best accuracy as it is giving the least error.

So, now we will apply degree = 3 to all the datasets available i.e., train and test.

In [122]:

In [125]:
results = permutation_importance(lin_model_poly, poly_X_train, y_train, scoring = 'neg_root_mean_squared_error', random_state = 1)

Bootstrap Sampling¶
In [181]:
concrete_XY = X.join(y)
Gradient Boosting Regressor¶
In [182]:
values = concrete_XY.values
# Number of bootstrap samples to create
n_iterations = 1000        
# size of a bootstrap sample
n_size = int(len(concrete_df_z) * 1)    

# run bootstrap
# empty list that will hold the scores for each bootstrap iteration
stats = list()   
for i in range(n_iterations):
    # prepare train and test sets
    train = resample(values, n_samples=n_size)  # Sampling with replacement 
    test = np.array([x for x in values if x.tolist() not in train.tolist()])  # picking rest of the data not considered in sample
    
    
     # fit model
    gbmTree = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=50)
    # fit against independent variables and corresponding target values
    gbmTree.fit(train[:,:-1], train[:,-1]) 
    # Take the target column for all rows in test set

    y_test = test[:,-1]    
    # evaluate model
    # predict based on independent variables in the test data
    score = gbmTree.score(test[:, :-1] , y_test)
    predictions = gbmTree.predict(test[:, :-1])  

    stats.append(score)
In [183]:
# plot scores

from matplotlib import pyplot
pyplot.hist(stats)
pyplot.show()
# confidence intervals
alpha = 0.95                             # for 95% confidence 
p = ((1.0-alpha)/2.0) * 100              # tail regions on right and left .25 on each side indicated by P value (border)
lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(stats, p))  
p = (alpha+((1.0-alpha)/2.0)) * 100
upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(stats, p))
print('%.1f confidence interval %.1f%% and %.1f%%' % (alpha*100, lower*100, upper*100))

95.0 confidence interval 82.0% and 87.1%

Thus, at 95% confidence interval the model trained by Gradient Boosting Regression will perfrom accurately between the range of 82% to 87.1%.

Thus, the following points can be inferred from this activity:

  • If we wish to use simple model to find the strength of the concrete then we need to use parameters based on polynomial features (as shown by a massive improvement when polynomial features were employed by Linear Regression as compared to Simple Linear Regression without the ploynomial features)

  • Whatever models we use to train and predict the data, the two most relevant features were: age and cement

  • Tree based models have performed better as compared to other models

  • We must always tune our parameters of a model before stating that so and so model is the best performng one (as was observed in the case of XG Boost Regression).

  • The third best performing model was one based on Gradient Boosting Regression. It has correctly predicted about 95.17% on training data and 90.15% on test data with a R2 score of 0.9016 and RMSE of 5.35. At 95% confidence level, the model has an accuracy in the range of 82% to 87.1%

  • The second best performing model was the one based on Random Forest Regression. It has correctly predicted about 98% on training data and 90.367% on test data with a R2 score of 0.90366 and RMSE of 5.29. At 95% confidence interval the model has an accuracy in the range of 84.4% and 90.5%

  • The best performing model was the one based on XG Boost Regression. It has correctly predicted about 98.49% on training data and 91.58% on test data with a R2 score of 0.9158 and RMSE of 4.94. Apart from this, at 95% confidenece interval the model has an accuracy in the range of 86.2% and 92%.
